---
<ComingSoonRoomLayout
  room="lectures"
  title="Lecture Hall"
  subtitle="Talks, presentations, demonstrations."
  sourceId="coming-soon-lectures"
>
  <p>
    The Lecture Hall will collect the talks the project's contributors have
    given, are giving, and will give — and, more importantly, will hand the
    materials over so anyone else can give the talk too. Recorded
    presentations and transcripts; slide decks for the standard one-hour
    overview, the legislative briefing, the school-board version, and the
    donor pitch; an outline of the long-form <em>Eighth Anchor</em>
    argument for an audience that wants the full case.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this room matters.</strong> The school-trust idea is among
    the most under-told stories in American public life. It will only be
    told at scale if many people learn to tell it. The Lecture Hall is the
    room that makes it possible for someone in Wyoming, or Nebraska, or
    Mississippi, to walk into their state's school-board meeting with a
    working version of the argument already in hand.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Give the talk in your state.</strong> A short "Talk Recipe"
    guide will walk a speaker through how to take the standard slide deck
    and tune it to a specific state — which figures to swap in, which
    cases to cite, which legislators to flag. Localization is the point.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Being planned.</strong> The first slide deck — the one-hour
    overview — goes up next.
  </p>
</ComingSoonRoomLayout>
